(b)

We denote Sunny as S, Cloudy as C, Rainy as R. And suppose today is sunny, we have 0.25 probability that tomorrow is R, 0.25 that tomorrow is C, 0.5 that tomorrow is S. Then for rainy, we have 0.5 that 2 days from now is R, 0.25 that 2days from now is C, 0.25 that 2 days from now is S. For C, we have 0.5 probabiltiy that two days later is R, 0 that is C, 0.5 that is S. For S, we have 0.25 that is R, 0.25 that is C, 0.5 that is S. So for 2 days from now it is Rainy, we have SRR= 0.250.5=0.125. SCR = 0.250.5 = 0.125, SSR = 0.50.25=0.125. The total probability is 0.1253=0.375. So for 2 days from now it is Cloudy, we have SRC = 0.250.25=0.0625, SCC = 0, SSC=0.50.25=0.125 The total probability is 0.0625+0.125=0.1875. So for 2 days from now it is Sunny, we have SRS = 0.25025=0.0625, SCS = 0.250.5 = 0.125, SSS = 0.5*0.5=0.25 And the total probabiltiy is 0.0625+0.125+0.25= 0.4375.

\[ \begin{aligned} &\text {From above we know that}\pi_0 = 0.4, \pi_1 = 0.2, \pi_2 = 0.4\\ &\text {And the distribution of }\pi \text{ would obey therule that}\\ &\ \pi_j = \sum_{k=0}^{N}\pi_kP_{kj} \text{ for j = 0,1,...N and } \sum_{i=0}^{N}\pi_i = 1\\ &\text {we can see here} \pi_0 = 0.5*\pi_0 + 0.5*\pi_1 + 0.25*\pi_2\\ &\ \pi_1 = 0.25*\pi_0 + 0.25*\pi_2 \text{ and } \pi_3 = 0.25*\pi_0 + 0.5*\pi_1 + 0.5 * \pi_2 \\ &\text{and } \sum_{i=0}^{N}\pi = 0.4+0.4+0.2 = 1 \\ &\text{so this is a stationary distribution. } \end{aligned} \]

\[ \begin{aligned} &\text{Assume }\alpha_i > 0 \text{for i = 1,..,6. Since P is regulard and must}\\ &\text{have positive entries, a limiting distribtion. }\\ &\ \pi = (\pi_0, ..., \pi_5) \text{exists and is the unique solution to the system of the questions}\\ &\ \pi_0 = \alpha_0\pi_0 + \pi_1, \pi_1 = \alpha_1\pi_0 + \pi_2,\\ &\ \pi_2 = \alpha_2\pi_0 + \pi_3,\pi_3 = \alpha_3\pi_0+\pi_4,\\ &\ \pi_4 =\alpha_4\pi_0+\pi_5, \pi_5=\alpha_5\pi_0\\ &\ \pi_0+\pi_1+\pi_2 + \pi_3 + \pi_4 + \pi_5 = 1\\ &\text{So we can get }\pi_0= \frac{1}{a_0+2a_1 + 3a_2 + 4a_3+5a_4+6a_5} \text{which is the limiting probability of being in state 0.} \end{aligned} \]

(a)

\[ \begin{aligned} &\text{We know that }f(y|\lambda) = \frac{e^{-y}\lambda^y}{y!}\text{ and }\lambda \text{follows gamma distribution}\\ &\text {We would have the likelihood function} L(\lambda) = \prod_{n=1}^{n}f(y|\lambda) = \frac{e^{-n\lambda}\lambda^{\sum_1^n y_i}}{(y!)^n}\\ &\text{and }\pi(\lambda)=\frac{\beta^\alpha}{\Gamma(\alpha)}\lambda^{\alpha-1}e^{-\beta\lambda} \text{ so we would know that }\pi(\lambda|y) \propto \frac{\beta^\alpha}{\Gamma(\alpha)}\lambda^{\alpha-1}e^{-\beta\lambda} *\frac{e^{-n\lambda}\lambda^{\sum_1^n y_i}}{(y!)^n}\\ &\ = \frac{e^{-(\beta+n)\lambda}*\lambda^{\alpha+\sum_1^n y_i -1}*\beta^\alpha}{(y!)^n\Gamma(\alpha)}\\ &\text{From this formula above we could see that the core part of }Gamma(\alpha+\sum_{i=1}^{n}y_i, \beta+n) \\ &\ \text{are in the expression. So }\pi(\lambda|y) \text{~} Gamma(\alpha+\sum_{i=1}^{n}y_i, \beta+n) \end{aligned} \]

(b)

\[ \begin{aligned} &\text{We know that the mean of gamma distribution is }E(\lambda|y) = \frac{\alpha+\sum_{i=1}^{n}y_i}{\beta+n}\\ &\text{And we suppose }w = \frac{\beta}{\beta+n} \text{ we can get }E(\lambda|y) = \frac{\alpha}{\beta+n}*\frac{\beta}{\beta} + \frac{\sum y_i}{\beta+n}*\frac{n}{n}\\ &\ = \frac{\beta}{\beta+n}*\frac{\alpha}{\beta}+\bar y*\frac{n}{\beta+n} \end{aligned} \]

(c)

\[ \begin{aligned} &\text{As n goes to infinity, } \frac{n}{\beta+n} \text{becomes dominate so the} E(\lambda|y)\\ &\text{ will be close to } \bar y. \end{aligned} \]

\[ \begin{aligned} &\text{1. Our proposal distributio is }N(\mu, \sigma)\\ &\text{2. generate }X_0 \text{from the proposal distribution}\\ &\text{3. Repeat until the chain has converged to stationary distribution according to the criterion }\\ &\text{4.Generate Y from the proposal distribution }\\ &\text{5. Generate U from uniform(0,1)}\\ &\text{6. compute } r =\frac{f(Y)g(X_t|Y)}{f(X_t)g(Y|X+t)}\\ &\text{7. If U<r, accept Y and set }X_{t+1} \text{=Y; otherwise} X_{t+1} = X_t\\ &\text{8. increment t} \end{aligned} \] ## (b)

(a)

\[ \begin{aligned} &\text{We have success of 24*20+6+7+7+14+18=532 success in total}\\ &\text{ and 5 fails in total.This follows geometric distribuiton }\\ &\text{and the total number of trails is 537. }\\ &\text{To find the posterior distirbuiton }f(\mu | x) \text{let f(p) = }1/(1-0)=1\\ &\ f(x|p) ={n \choose x} p^x(1-p)^{n-x}\\ &\ f(x) = \int_0^1 {n \choose x} p^x(1-o)^{n-x} dp\\ &\ = {n \choose x} \int_0^1 p^x(1-o)^{n-x} dp \\ &\text{Let q = 1-p}\\ &\ f(x) ={n \choose x} \int_0^1 p^x(1-p)^{n-x} dp \\ &\ ={n \choose x} Beta(n-x+1, x+1)\\ &\ f(p|x) = \frac{f(x|p)f(p)}{f(x)}\\ &\ = \frac{{n \choose x} p^x(1-p)^{n-x} }{{n \choose x} Beta(n-x+1, x+1)}\\ &\ = \frac{p^x(1-p)^{n-x}}{Btea(n-x+1, x+1)}\\ &\ = \frac{p^532 (1-p)^5}{Beta(533,6)}\\ &\text {Since }\mu = \frac{p}{1-p}, p=\frac{\mu}{1+\mu}\\ &\ F_M(\mu)=P(\frac{p}{1-p} \leq \mu)=F_p(\frac{\mu}{1+\mu})\\ &\ f(\mu|x) =\frac{1}{(1+\mu)^2}\frac{(1/(1+\mu))^{532}(1-(1/(1+u)))^5}{Btea(533, 6)}\\ &\text{Algorithm: 1. choose Gamma as our proposal distrbution }g(.|X_t)\\ &\text{2.Generae }X_0 \text{from the proposal distribution }\\ &\text {3.Repeat until th chain has converged to stationary distribuiton according to some criterion}\\ &\text{4. Generate Y from proposal distribution}\\ &\text{5. Generate U from uniform(0,1)}\\ &\text{6. Compute} r=\frac{f(Y)g(X_t|Y)}{f(X_t)g(Y|X_t)}\\ &\text{7. if U<r, accept Y and set}X_{t+1}=Y, \text{otherwise, set }X_{t+1}=X_t\\ &\text {8.increment t. } \end{aligned} \]

(b)

f.mu <- function(x){
  exp(lbeta(533,6)+532*log(x)-532*log(1+x)-7*log(1+x))
}
fr <- function(x,y){
  a <- 532*(log(y)-log(x))
  b <- 539*(log(1+x)-log(1+y))
  return(exp(a+b))
}
m <- 10000
x <- numeric(m)
a <- 5
x[1] <- rlnorm(1)
k <- 0
u <- runif(m)
for (i in 2:m){
  xt <- x[i-1]
  y <- rgamma(1, shape=a, rate=a/xt)
  r <- fr(xt, y)*dgamma(xt, shape=a, rate=a/y)/dgamma(y, shape=a, rate=a/xt)
  if(u[i] <=r){
    x[i] <- y
  }else {
    x[i] <- xt
    k <- k+1
  }
}

acf

acf(X)

We can tell that when a=5, the chain is mixing well.
